  "prompt": "How is the Lewis dot structure for Ch3OH determined?",
  "response": "Here's how to determine the Lewis dot structure for CH3OH (methanol):\n\n**1. Calculate the Total Number of Valence Electrons:**\n\n*   Carbon (C):  4 valence electrons\n*   Hydrogen (H): 1 valence electron (and there are 4 of them = 4 x 1 = 4 electrons)\n*   Oxygen (O): 6 valence electrons\n\nTotal: 4 + 4 + 6 = 14 valence electrons\n\n**2. Determine the Central Atom(s):**\n\n*   Carbon is generally a central atom (it can form 4 bonds).\n*   Oxygen is also a central atom in this molecule.  Oxygen can form 2 bonds and is bonded to the carbon.  Oxygen is more electronegative than carbon and hydrogen, so it can also handle some lone pairs.\n*   Hydrogen is *always* terminal (it can only form one bond).\n\n**3. Draw the Basic Skeletal Structure:**\n\nThe arrangement will be H3C-O-H.  Place the atoms next to each other that are bonded:\n\n```\n  H\n  |\nH-C-O-H\n  |\n  H\n```\n\n**4. Add Single Bonds:**\n\nDraw single bonds between the central atom(s) and the terminal atoms. Each single bond represents 2 electrons:\n\n```\n  H\n  |\nH-C-O-H\n  |\n  H\n```\n*There are 5 single bonds which represents 5 x 2 = 10 electrons that have been used.\n\n**5.  Distribute Remaining Electrons as Lone Pairs:**\n\n*   Subtract the number of electrons used in bonding from the total number of valence electrons: 14 (total) - 10 (bonding) = 4 electrons remaining.\n*   Place the remaining electrons as lone pairs on the *more electronegative* atoms first (excluding Hydrogen, which never gets lone pairs). Oxygen is more electronegative than Carbon.  Add two lone pairs to oxygen:\n\n```\n  H\n  |\nH-C-O-H\n  |\n  H\n  . .\n```\n*There are now 2 lone pairs on the oxygen, which equals 4 electrons.\n\n**6. Check the Octet Rule:**\n\n*   **Carbon:** Has 8 electrons around it (4 single bonds).\n*   **Oxygen:** Has 8 electrons around it (2 single bonds and 2 lone pairs).\n*   **Hydrogen:** Has 2 electrons around it (1 single bond) - follows the duet rule.\n\n**7. The Final Lewis Structure:**\n\nThe final Lewis dot structure for CH3OH is:\n\n```\n  H\n  |\nH-C-O-H\n  |\n  H\n..\n..\n```\n\n**Summary of the Steps:**\n\n1.  Calculate total valence electrons.\n2.  Determine central atom(s).\n3.  Draw skeletal structure.\n4.  Add single bonds.\n5.  Distribute remaining electrons as lone pairs, starting with the most electronegative atoms (except Hydrogen).\n6.  Check the octet rule (or duet rule for H).\n7.  If octets are not satisfied on central atoms, form multiple bonds. (Not needed in this case)\n\n**Important Notes:**\n\n*   Hydrogen *never* has lone pairs. It always forms only one bond.\n*   Oxygen usually has two bonds and two lone pairs.\n*   Carbon usually has four bonds and no lone pairs.\n*   Electronegativity plays a key role in determining where to place lone pairs.\n",
